Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner cold cuts
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, where being overweight affects 9% of the school population and obesity affects 5%.
Obese children mostly come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, according to current research.
It re-demonstrates the importance of the environment where it grows for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obsessive children feed, for example, on sausages at least twice as often as children in normal-weight families.
By dinner, more than 19% of obese people had dined chips the day before the test, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a fluke."
In families of overweight children there is no habit of playing sports, which is applicable to most current families, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and nearly 900 Basic Education children from across the Czech Republic participated in it.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a fluke", supported by the General Health Insurance Company and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th year.
Proper diet and plenty of family exercise are determining factors, which significantly decrease the number of overweight and even obese children.
"Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five meals a day according to the regimen: breakfast, lunch, lunch, afternoon tea and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet," one of the survey results.
No breakfast but cold cuts for dinner
Specialists warn that, in a healthy development, details are also important, which also count, such as having a fixed time for family breakfast.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of schoolchildren's families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to find out that in 10% of households nothing is breakfast.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that in families of obese children, insane fries are consumed much more frequently.
Almost all - regardless of weight - drink daily sweet soft drinks (70%).
As a rule, more than 40% of the children surveyed sport, however, among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Get your diet
The next phase of the study made it possible for the chosen kids (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15, from the point of view of healthy eating, are far removed from ideal."
Favourite foods include pasta, meat and sweets
"The popularity of sweet soft drinks is mostly alarming," the final report of the study warns.
As a main meal, the pasta is carried away and the poultry is closely followed.
Practically, children always reject legume and a taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Switching to healthy habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
"In the control group of study participants, who completed the questionnaire after the end of the prevention program "Obesity is not a fluke", in many cases there was a major change in favor of the principles of healthy eating", the results of the study are noted.
It draws attention, for example, to sweet soft drinks, where many children would begin to prefer regular water.
Children would also choose poultry and fish for main meal more frequently in the questionnaire and restrict consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
