Need for Speed: The Run competes all over America.
Review
A trip, initially carefree, is complicated by a series of carelessness of a routine journey during tomorrow's shift.
To some extent expectations were met, but this is useless if nothing extraordinary was actually intended to be done.
The new installment, to which The Run is added, raised high expectations already before its premiere.
He promised that he would give new airs to the old Need for Speed racing saga and, following what is shown, appears as a game that should not end up being again an action genre.
We also feel curious to know what the inserted scenes would look like, where the main character descends from the car and walks on his own foot.
As is often the case in NFS series, the results do not vary much from what we expected.
There are races that can be given as acceptable, but in the total count points are lost due to absurd failures, which have been appearing in the series for years.
In reality, they cannot even be called errors, but rather the incomprehensible degana of programmers.
The adventure starts very well.
You are introduced to a story, whose protagonist, Jack, has certain personal problems; to solve them, he is offered to take part in an illegal race across America.
You sit behind the wheel on the west coast in San Francisco, and your mission is to get the first ones to New York.
The idea is to offer something interesting.
The route is divided into ten stages and then more than fifty races.
It follows that each race takes place on a different route and the stages are located in different environments, which are quite diverse and interesting.
That way, you don't even remotely get the feeling that the game always offers the same thing.
Some of the environments are even pleasing to the eye, although the technical level of the chart is equivalent to that of previous installments in the series.
So it's nothing of the other world.
But the walk through the desert, the fall landscape or the high snow-covered mountains produce a very pleasant visual effect.
In addition, races are diversified from time to time by an atypical element.
So, for example, in the desert you will find a sandstorm that decreases visibility.
Instead, in the mountains you have to be careful not to be buried by an avalanche.
According to that, each of the races is very well developed.
There's only a couple of models, but that's enough.
For a moment, you try to overtake a required number of opponents (normal in a classic race), then try to buy time (timed classic duel) and then a duel against a single opponent awaits you.
In the midst of all this, sometimes the police appear, which only makes things even more difficult.
The novelty is the landscapes outside the car.
Interactive animations are presented when Jack, in most cases, has to escape someone and you have to help him, always pressing the button just at the right time.
Nothing complicated.
Surprisingly, however, there are far fewer landscapes in the game than you would expect (specifically there are only three).
But the end result is positive, because this element does not become annoying and, in the context already mentioned, is one of the elements that make the game more interesting.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous episodes.
That means that to this day it is no longer a big deal, but it cannot be said to be bad.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you can search elsewhere.
But a race conceived with a lot of action is very good for this style of driving, although you can find something better among the games of the competition.
So far, everything's in order.
But problems arise after a certain amount of time.
Unlike the right driving models, the same is no longer the case with collisions.
Games like this can't be expected to recreate complicated deformations and collisions, but in fact before a hit against any object, you can't predict how your car will react, so not everything is in order.
It is typical that, when you make a very tight overtaking or drive the car with normal traffic, there are only slight frictions, but in other almost identical situations, your car ends up doing uncontrolled pirouettes.
Or it even ends up totally destroyed.
Thanks to the reset system, there are no big problems, but it can put you in a bad mood.
Resets are programmed in such a way that when you suffer an accident or get out of the track, the game restores you to the last rescue point on the track.
However, only five resets are available in each race.
If you consume them all, you have to restart the race from the beginning.
So it's just a help in case something doesn't go well, but it's not very trusting.
Sometimes, even resetting doesn't help, it just helps to learn the given stage from memory.
A big disadvantage of the game is that the same facts are repeated in different places.
In some curves, for example, you have to enter in a specific way; otherwise, they are impossible to take.
Other times you will find "civilian" vehicles somewhere always with the same configuration, even if you are the first, fifth or arrive five minutes before or after.
This makes you rage especially in situations, when you see that two cars that go to meet in opposite directions, your opponent advances smoothly, but when you arrive, you must turn or brake.
It's the same when you arrive, because it's programmed because the "surprise" will always happen right under your nose.
Opponents also have one more advantage.
Throughout the game you will reach places where, regardless of the moment, you will always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
This also happens at the end of the game, on a long bridge, which is even more shocking.
Your opponent must arrive before you, at whatever price.
When it goes in front of you, it makes it difficult for you to see the cars that come from the front, so at first you can make porridge the car.
You can understand the idea of creating a game with maximum doses of suspense and adrenaline, but the execution is so apparent that it will surely disappoint you right away.
And it's a shame, because even if the travel model is simple, the game is fun and action-action, so it's often not possible to follow in detail what's going on or where.
And it doesn't really matter, if the merit takes the idea with fifty exclusive tracks or the ranking in the race so that there is no boredom, or anything else.
An unusual idea is the change of cars during races.
You have to be attentive to the gas pumps next to the road, because right there you have to change cars, although in the vast majority of cases what you have will suffice.
Cars fall into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, American strong cars for straight highways and exotic supercars for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain roads.
In addition, the main narrative thread also appears a thread of parallel challenges, that is, there are races in specific places that you will know for the stories.
Here you will get not only medals, but also experience points for your profile, which serves both challenges and stories.
When reaching the top level, the driver opens up several possibilities, starting with the car and finishing with funds for the profile.
At the same time, an online Autolog feature is connected, which compares your results with those of other players and provides other community functions.
One of the most difficult elements to understand is how the last race in history is made.
With the car you reach the tunnel of the subway (pass), where you start running in the dark along the tracks (pass).
The speedometer marks you between 150 and 200 km/h (pass) and suddenly from behind you you get the convoy of the subway and takes you ahead.
In the writing we will surely have a discussion about this for several days, about whether during the programming of the game none even thought a little or if the authors really take us for a bunch of fools.
The technical part of the game is nothing extraordinary, but at least the overall visual effects result in most pleasant, sometimes even superb, visual effects.
Well, what a pity that, in the most tense moments, image quality is reduced and sometimes in a serious way.
This mainly affects accidents where many participants are involved, when continuous image quality is no longer valid.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In order to please most of the youth group, the soundtrack belongs to the category "each of their father and mother", but it can be assumed that no one would buy the game just for their music.
The final feeling of Need for Speed: The Run is therefore quite confusing.
If the game avoided absolutely silly bugs, we'd have trouble claiming that The Run is the best NFS game of recent years.
It gives the feeling that the game is not finished.
The fun is assured, but be prepared because mistakes will hit you in the eyes with the strength of some airport reflectors.
Carolina University choirs will participate in the "Velvet Students" concert.
The joint celebration of International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution as a musical experience will take place for the third time at the Festa Academica festival.
During it, twenty choirs from secondary and university centers will be presented.
The festival revolves around two concerts on November 17.
"Carolina University has a high stake in the festival."
Among the current choirs are the choir of the Faculty of Pedagogy and the Faculty of Humanities, on the committee of the festival is the rector Václav Hampl," said the head of the organization, Jakub Aaloun.
The summit of the entire festival is the free entry for all audiences to the concert of the high school choirs, which will be held on March 17 at 14 hours in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program features the participation of Czech jazzman Karel R.I.ka and his Celebration Jazz Mass.
In the evening, the "Velvet Students" concert will be held at the municipal house venues in Vynohrady, featuring university choirs, including the Carolina Uninversity Choir.
The Academic Festa aims not only to celebrate International Student Day worthily and to remember the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music to the public at the highest level and promote collaborative creation among young people.
The main organizer is the Czech Coral Union in collaboration with the Jan Kepler High School Institute.
All acts were supported by Prague Mayor Bohuslav Svoboda and Carolina University Rector Václav Hampl.
The Festival will run between 16 and 20 November between Prague and Pardubice.
The calendar offers, in addition to the celebratory concerts, a whole series of musical events, improvised student shows and morning concerts.
More information can be found on the festival page www.festaacademica.cz
