Brand story:
Innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone were looking for a term that would define IBM's strategy with great precision, the nearest one would be "long term."
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet it has been a hundred years since its founding.
The basis of this long-term character was laid by the first head of the firm, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He has already coined the motto that many problems in the world have a solution if people are willing to think.
Its motto "Think!" became its label, around which the life of the giant future will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully raised company culture.
"For us, IBM implies long-term thinking, a continuous movement going forward.
IBM has survived and prospered for a hundred years for that reason, because it remained true to its basic principles, but without fear of the changes around it.
This has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We hope to thrive even more in our second century," said current company director Samuel J. Palmisano during its anniversary.
