How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia at the time: Oedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time in most cases sold travel only to the socialist bloc, as trips to the West were severely restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and the travels of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, other than the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies in those times also offered trips to the West, but one had to line up with a sleeping bag and spend the night like this, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not conceded to "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The Czechs' way of travelling has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was the no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is nna great paradox, of which today we are no longer aware, the fact that to the currently favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of the Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s visa waiver was imposed to travel to neighbouring Western European states, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not look fed up with excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, groups of Czechs slept in the parks in tents in Paris, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of Czechs at the time was to take food (preserves, cold cuts, etc.) with them to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, buy freely Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and so did average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in demand for travel.
With the increased demand for travel began agencies, starting in 1997 regularly, to prepare trips using charter connections, which caused travel prices to fall incredibly compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts on passenger volume.
By the late 1990s, the Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the US, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as far back as 2000, when the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, thanks to enormous demand, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights depart every year with Czech tourists to far and hot countries. This winter you will already fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100 thousand Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, symbolizing our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. removed visas for Czech tourists, rising among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, more than 15,000 Czech kronor per head have been spent on overseas trips, including expenses at the place of stay.
