While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of his time preceding his attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing social media groups.
After this summer's tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - just log in to Facebook.
"We realized it wasn't that hard to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British DEMOS study centre.
Facebook's stash of personal information is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy – the way sellers have been using it for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then targeted them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes toward violence, and optimism about their own future.
Arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – all without leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way to do an investigation," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those left behind the computer screen."
DEMOS' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming an important new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health problems to social trends as expressed in the Likes, wall messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating a research boom, boosting the number of academic papers with the site name in the title to nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to go through the game, and they'd never let you access," Bartlett says.
"Facebook eliminates all that -- you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that college students who talked about their drunken exploits on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that student peers, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student who posts too many status updates with their drunkenness.
"You can't treat a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of the Center for Health, Behavior and Child Development at the Seattle Institute for Child Research, the Washington Post said.
"We have found a way to identify at-risk children who would not otherwise be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "clicking" its own population to get data.
The Site Data Team has produced statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of voter turnout midway through the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - advocates of digital freedom have long argued that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - the sacrifice for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is an open bar for everyone.
"I don't think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study he conducted with the public Facebook walls of students.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there's the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know that some of a user's profile information and wall messages are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn says.
That's why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes a paper clip and pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
"There's no substitute for entering the real world and talking to real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about the social - and a lot of the social still happens offline."
