He was certainly a self-known designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a yonki of flowcharts - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease that consists in thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
By that time it had been only 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and was already working hard at his new computer company NeXT, awaiting popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transportation.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full vhS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly reissued footage is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview that arrives at Landmark theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose their technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs' perfectionism surfaces, where he seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing him to move faster toward the most important issues or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do well and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It's one thing to read portum reviews of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in business, I always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers they give you invariably are, "Oh, that's just the way it's done."
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs takes your efforts to simplify Apple accounting in detail.
