Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
About big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple's renaissance, Jobs prophetically foresaw how many industry leaders would stumble into his vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make photocopiers and printers better, so what?"
You have a monopoly on market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it's these kinds of people who end up running companies and product managers are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position rots because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire IT industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There is an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the big idea evolves, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can't make electrons, glass makes them, robots make them, factories do them.
