How to spot a lie
A look at the latest headlines tells us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment allegations with several women; each side accuses of lying to the other.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone claiming to U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself with his quickly demented debated by the irrefutable test.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget president Bill Clinton's media circus by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating on school and college exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given test responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On any other day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, a lot of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies," is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the last six decades in prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the investigation is that the old myths about lying have been disputed.
Liars do look into their eyes.
They don't always stutter, babble, blush or restless.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and times.
I spent several years proning scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detecting deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, handling their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "lies oriented toward themselves," while women tell more "otherwise-oriented" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than non-married people (but the lies they often tell tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline".
Helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
You'd better know if someone normally hits your foot all the time so you don't make unfair accusations when you see your feet pounding in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal, and nonverbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavior groups as alarm signals, not evidence of deception.
Cheating people can freeze the upper body as they try to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a "post-view relief" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Interrogators often falsely see that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up and used the past time while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
Cheating people can also use a differentiating language: "I didn't have sex with that woman. Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... up to what I know... to my mind."
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
