Climate adversity slowed the economy
During mario López Valdez's first year of management, unemployment and informality have increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment fell and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in sinaloa's economic history, this is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled with change, which generated high expectations regarding advances in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, instead there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
February's low temperatures, in addition to causing million-dollar losses for the agricultural sector, limited the chances of the state economy growing, caused a contraction in overall economic activity of 3.6% in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic 31.16 percent drop in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the frost impact report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares cultivated were damaged, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent had partial damage, the main sinister crops being vegetables, maize and chickpea.
The fall in economic activity has led, until November, to a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was observed accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloenses were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the economically active population , for the second quarter the rate became 5.28 percent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 percent, a rate that in number of people throws more than 74 thousand unemployed Sinaloans, an increase from the first half of 18,969 individuals.
Lower liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out since public policy.
"What is being seen is unemployment growth that has to do with a number of factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market from the effects of a resource constraint by the legislation passed in Congress to combat money laundering, and for people who grab dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work , invest them and use them in something," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes noted that in the increase in unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state looking for work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first by the difficulties of entering, and second because they already have a lot of difficulty finding work, these people are staying and demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise" Said.
Informality
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population occupied in the state works without being listed as a worker before any social security institution.
Coupled with unemployment and informality, another of the state's labor lags are low wages, the entity has the lowest remuneration in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Security.
The average monthly income for Sinaloan workers was, as of September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, at 7,375 pesos.
IED shrinkage
Coupled with falling economic activity and growth in unemployment, during 2011 there has been the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of the Economy from January to June on state EDI totaled $630,697, representing a fall of 87.74 per cent from $5 million,143,312 per cent during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Ministry of Economic Development of the State Government counts a total investment of 17 billion pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
Faced with the economic downturn, the state government in July requested the state congress to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be earmarked for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to revive the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2.6 billion pesos , and until November they have not seen the benefits of borrowing in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, mario López Valdés' first year of government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 the harmonization of wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself, was lacking.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, it lacked to align the effort of all and above all the good progress already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better" Expressed.
Economic slowness
Loredo López stated that events such as the frosts of the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frost, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows us to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had" Mentioned.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronial Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he stated that it is required to channel the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"Overall we have observed that work has been underway, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that the full potential of Sinaloa's material and human resource is detonous," he said.
Work to be done
