Corte validates "analog blackout" in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional disputes brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog blackout" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes needed to invalidate it did not meet.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to realize the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for not reaching a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft judgment, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
In favor of the project they voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero hem.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree, and by admitting the claims, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions therein arranged for the digital transition.
The full minister decided to dismiss also the demand brought by the Chamber of Deputies, without going into discussion of the project, also by Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Minister-President said he did not agree with the project's arguments that the federal executive could not structure through general rules measures for the public administration to prepare.
"I also do not believe that doing so would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector belongs to the federal executive, who has as a constitutional mandate, the rectory of the state.
Replacing analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, resulting in better use of radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone change, he argued, would be to put off the benefits of digitization, which involves a decision in the public interest, which has not only a technical dimension, "as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he emphasized, "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic rectory of the State, encompassing a group of powers that the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive".
It recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the digital transition, and had done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, which in any way invades the sphere of competence of Congress, because compliance with the laws issued by the Legislative is being provided in the administrative sphere, he said.
