The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed Italy on the brink of economic disaster
Italian pm Mario Monti will meet on Wednesday with Italy's president to introduce the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet on Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present to the president the outcome of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he would be able to form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "frame is now well delineated," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, as Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the shocked confidence in Italy.
Stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability put the yield on Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7%, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting Monti: "We said we would support this government very much."
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were significantly driven by the backing of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told the press.
The support of the LDA, Italy's largest party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in their efforts could lead to a devastating new attack by financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure by warning that Monti's failure would be a disaster.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups on Monday, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
He'll end his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels a few times ache of uncertainty as to whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescuing Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone's current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before advancing the election.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that he should be made up only of technicians, an indication of his qualms about a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources noted that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
