The group is located in the South American wing of its two-decade-long celebration tour and on Sunday 20 will make its only stopover in Central America.
That day they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., with the angel band The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which is in The Nation on the Internet.
For your Costa Rican fans, it's a dream come true that Pearl Jam is going to play in Costa Rica, are you aware of what your fans are living?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it's been great.
I have been to Costa Rica only once and on vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we're going to be able to stay there for a few days.
So we're excited to bring our music there.
I ask you because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live intensely in the days before.
What do you say to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying by our side throughout all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played over the last 21 years happened over the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of gigantic shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we're really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; that's how we found out, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they have been delivering huge shows with many songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
As we've never played there before, then we don't have any restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best possible show with a good variety of songs; we'll try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's this all about?
I think it's partially because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to choose which songs to play each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we have been not playing for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we could have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting to us and, therefore, I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of experience.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've accomplished?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined that we'd be in a big rock band and doing it for over 20 years makes it look like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and love to create music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world that we always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean to you to have been a fundamental part of the emergence of grunge?
It's always been an honor to be part of that group of big bands.
We are very close friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's amazing when a move comes from a group of friends and it's rare.
Occasionally, a band emerges from a city, but it's much stranger when five or ten bands leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to be friends with all of them yet and we're honored to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It's also very strange that a band like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which alone is much longer than many bands last.
First of all, I think we are all lucky to still be alive and, secondly, we all care about each other.
