MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
He leads Social Security research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is leading research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity' protocol, which will allow markers associated with being overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialty Hospital of the National Medical Center Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the research is invited to participate the population whether or not they are entitled, go to the participating sports units of IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to the minors, every Saturday from 8:00 hours.
He emphasized that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to understand the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
At the time of World Diabetes Day on 14 November, he stated that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on food.
They will also be asked about physical activity and history of disease families, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure intake, determination of glucose, triglyceride, cholesterol and insulin and genetic levels are applied to all participants (genes that are associated with childhood obesity are sought).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was an increase, for boys, of 77 per cent in obesity, and girls 47 per cent; in terms of overweight there was also a dramatic rise,' the IMSS specialist said.
It indicated that the justification for finding the markers was based on the country's population differing from others by their genetic history.
On average, Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African, and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translate into the inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive evaluation of children, which allows to detect if they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said the presence of dark folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic and even prediabete alterations.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors give it in writing to parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, i.e. the increased consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) high in fats and proteins and the genetics discussed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at UNAM's Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a better-performing mixture, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the pavement were taken care of, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, warned, who ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt pavement is adequate , potholes could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated altogether.
At his conference A technological view of potholes, given in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, released that the laboratory in charge develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphalt, and others of low molecular weight, called malthenos, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that on the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that makes up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer opined.
Above the asphalt folder, abounded, is placed a last layer called a rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, an sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with vehicle tires, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt folder and provide friction along the way.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the rolling folder also requires to be of the right thickness and care must be taken of the material from which it is made.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the terrain gets wet, the water diffuses inside the folder and is difficult to get out, causing a softening of all layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a pothole, he said, the first to wear out is the tread film and only after the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but is a process that should be taken care of the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always be in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is met, to prevent potholes from forming frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already even on the market and allow to repair potholes easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
