So was the work of the caleño who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali went into history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4th a CTI lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the Farc's top boss: "Alfonso Cano", through the matching of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists working in the CTI section, that week it was the turn of "availability" to Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the judicial investigation area for 21 years.
At the start of his career, González worked in municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to enter for more than five days in the jungle to reach the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, specialized in lophoscopy, which is the study of frictional skin, that is, the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano to Eliazar warned him to wear clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
On Friday night he left for the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected of being from the man leading the world's oldest guerrillas, so he was asked to carry the decadactilar card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was located, he did not recognize him for his physical appearance, as he was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local peasant, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the body's fingerprints to those on the card.
His eye did not fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the chief of the Farc.
In search of the footprint
For a dactyloscopist of the Sikhín de Cali, President Juan Manuel Santos' recognition of Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operative against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin for error, that can become key in solving crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, lophoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many criminals present fake cards or do not have papers.
We take the fingerprint and look for them in the database.
The investigator recounted that, in a robbery case, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, as there the thief had rested his hand to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to make a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the print from the whole hand and identify the offender, who had been involved in different thefts," he recalled.
Fingerprints can also rule out or reassert suspects in murder cases.
They recently found a dead man, with bottles of liquor around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a relative could be a suspect in the crime and, indeed, a print on the bottle matched.
Although this doesn't guarantee it was the killer, it does place him at the crime scene.
A CTI fingerprinter explained that in objects "fingerprints are taken out with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Logging.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," the CTI expert said.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the TV show CSI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything you touch becomes a mark.
However, if it can be used, if the respective check is performed.
The "outraged" defy authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters crowded in front of Zuccotti Square for camping.
A large part served the eviction order and moved to a nearby paruqe.
Members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities on Tuesday as they tried to re-enter, under the protection of a court order, Manhattan Square from where they were evicted in the early hours of the morning and trying to occupy another Big Apple park.
Hundreds of protesters crowded off Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access thanks to a court order that allows the "outraged" to camp again at the site, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction by occupying a park further north of the city, where there have been further arrests.
"Our idea is that if the court doesn't allow us to camp again in the square, we're going to settle somewhere else and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through peaceful sit-ins and demonstrations," said one of the spokesmans for the "Occupy Wall Street" movement, Mark Bray.
Bray detailed that the "outraged" response to the eviction of his camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting forced evacuation of the site and allowing protesters to stay camped.
In addition, the "outraged" proceeded to occupy a new park located at the confluence of downtown Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which linkes New York and New Jersey, and owned by Trinity Church Parish.
For at least an hour they managed to take the place, but then the police came and proceeded to arrest some of the protesters, although Bray could not confirm the specific figure, while assured Efe that he saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization says that several hundred people had settled at that point, where a delegation of religious leaders has already moved in support of the members of the movement and has tried to mediate with the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a privately owned precinct - is still closed pending a court hearing scheduled for this Tuesday in which the legality of this morning's evacuation must be analysed.
Some of the protesters displaced there carried and distributed copies of that court order at this hour and even handed them over to the officers guarding the square, prompting "some small clashes," said Bray, who reported that some officers beat the protesters.
The court order prohibits the authorities from evicting Members of Occupy Wall Street or applying "laws that were published after the occupation began or prohibiting protesters from re-accessing the park with shops or other properties they previously used."
Mayor Bloomberg indicated to the press that, because of this court order, the city had suspended the reopening of space to the public and protesters, who he warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to re-install with tents and sleeping bags.
The councilor personally defended the early-morning eviction of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which about 200 arrests were made and decided because the protesters were "breaking the law."
Bloomberg explained that he gave the order to evacuate the square because it was becoming "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, to harm others", since "some businesses had received threats" and neighbors feared "for their quality of life".
"This morning's eviction was disgusting and shows that Bloomberg is more interested in preserving financial interests than those of American workers," added the movement's spokesman, who accused the mayor of "disrespecting freedom of expression."
The leaders of "Occupy Wall Street" also indicated that they plan to organize "great actions" by Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions, to commemorate the two months that the protests lasted, which began on September 17.
