A committee of experts says euthanasia and assisted suicide should be legalized
Canadians live denying death, says Royal Society of Canada report
On palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and physicians to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not just in cancer cases.
Canadian society lives denying death.
In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they wish to die and make arrangements for this purpose.
It is one of the conclusions of an imposing report by the Royal Society of Canada, which was attended by six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and physician.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code in such a way as to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient considers such an option and has been competent to make the decision.
To begin with, experts cite a recent Economist Intelligence Unit survey that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks tenth, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death."
On medication or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada indicate.
And even though most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded by Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not coincide with the federal government's position, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Penal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not caused an abuse of their application, that is, the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with non-competent persons or that they have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, more excesses were observed in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians, pro-euthanasia
Let us remember that 85% of Canadians have already spoken out in favour of euthanasia, as they believe it would allow people whose near death would alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid survey.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people have less value.
For people who have practiced assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believe that a process should not be initiated against them.
