Energy policy:
facts should be worth more than dogmas
If there is one issue that cannot be dealt with considering short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate for an electoral meeting to be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if you study all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic developments will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing scarcity of fossil resources will need to be alleviated to continue producing electricity continuously, not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear power.
That is not the case either of Belgium, which subjects its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor of Switzerland, which is only intended to build next-generation power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, move forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, on the other hand, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a interrupted power plant following the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such discourse.
Berlin's election is going to lead to an increase in the price of electricity, increased energy dependence on the increased need for imported gas, particularly from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal-fired power plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
European champion in the wind sector, from which he obtains 30% of his electricity, he is also one of the great users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, their CO2 emissions and the price of their electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from Europe's cheapest electricity.
For this reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would detract from the wonderful statements about the re-industrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not express opposition in principle to this type of energy, as the polls show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets that can create non-relocatable jobs.
If France were to decide to abandon nuclear power, it would mean the slaughter of much of these SMEs and the loss of EUR 6 billion per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to run sixty years, when its manufacturer's collapse is planned?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source either.
Areva's development of low-CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear power, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing power plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not have consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to reactor design and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented reach, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, just as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is being studied by all the electrical actors who wish to build a power plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for areva and EDF competitors, as it would set them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan manoeuvres dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
Nicolas Sarkozy's immigration policy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the Libération newspaper of 23 May) proclaiming from the past that France "does not need foreign talent, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this subject, there is quite a lot of consensus between left and right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both left and right shared fear of invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with regard to immigrants.
In his programme, Francois Hollande merely includes banalities, stating that co-development will allow the "migration problem" to be solved.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically it comes out very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the latest knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth , wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that immigrants can replace domestic workers, particularly the low-skilled, by pushing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that immigrants are actually rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and mainly practice professions in under-employment sectors.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would struggle to work in a country that lacks anaesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of nationals to positively influence the wages and employment of nationals.
Taking into account the above, Giovanni Peri estimated that a 1% increase in migration flows represents an increase in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to brainstorming and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, PayPal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, providing on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of EUR 150,000 to public budgets on average throughout his or her life.
At the beginning of his tenure, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go look for the growth points he lacked "with his teeth".
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
Europe invented democracy, it just needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the twentieth century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that, in order for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be sufficient to exercise the vote and as directly as possible.
We know, from Napoleon the Little One, that it was something thought out.
Universal suffrage, while a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an "instrument of oppression," as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are living in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
