Listening to Republican candidates for presidential candidates, voters might think so.
For a few days now, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the other candidates have been making more and more thunderous statements and shortcuts on foreign policy, traditionally a strong point for Republicans.
The slogans, often unfounded, about China, Iran, aid to Israel are extended.
Mitt Romney, the best-placed candidate on the grand old party designation, has threatened to take the Chinese to the WTO and denounce them "for currency manipulation," a key issue in an America exasperated by the migration of entire fragments of their sector to Asia.
It doesn't matter if that involves the explosion of a trade war, he said.
