Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea fund, has already been put into service.
You must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the Baltic shores, between the orchestra's music and a delicate law firm, at the opening of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that directly connects Russia with Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his counterpart in the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have turned together the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first of 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012 which will provide a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, i.e. sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents airs of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land course by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to shut it down by closing access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact," in reference to hitler-Stalin's alliance to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has achieved greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to make its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large gas consumers and increasingly limited reserves triumph.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unies us organically," Francois Fillon confirmed during the pipeline's opening, demonstrating the extent to which the big contracts in the gas sector are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of Gazprom's managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect against ship anchors.
It rests at the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," says Jens Muller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extreme measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was envisaged in the waters of Sweden, but project managers resigned from it by seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state-owned society to settle permanently at sea off its coast.
"In the event of a breakdown, we will interrupt the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Muller.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But builders find a leak unlikely, as they have planned joints that are expected to leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is inserted into the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to run for fifty years without any repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by Germany's E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as The Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint company, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to that company, for a renewable twenty-five-year period, all gas transport capabilities.
"Gazprom will be paid for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported," says Jens Muller.
Pipeline construction financing has been carried out by 30% by shareholder input and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom assumes the risk of expenses on its own.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors are in place to measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back a taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its leaves broken white, as aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to release a book of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant to the company, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the stool.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to today's taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the twentieth century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Gone is the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, as the notebook attracts both businessmen, students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-spirited and educated.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its early days, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard caps, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: handbags, agendas, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Daunting?
"No," says Eric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made since fifteen years is considerable.
"Back then, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, much remains to be done."
It is worth mentioning that the disabled unemployed continue to face numerous barriers to access to employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the cru shred of the problem," says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; people's mindset moves forward, but too slowly.
An April study by the ASSOCIATION IMS-Entreprendre for cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual deficient".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are a long way from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created a lot of pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their workforce, compared to 82% of companies between 100 and 199 workers.
Hazard: "A Joy"
About to face the Bleus on Tuesday night (20:45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens don't hide the pleasure of this friendly match.
We dare not say that there was collusion between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting next to each other, on the stand of the Stade de France auditorium, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have really made peace.
Five months after his striker's gesture of grudge against Turkey, the Belgian nationalist has nothing but praise for him.
"I was very happy for Eden, for his progress and because he is Belgian."
"I want to move forward," Lille's striker replies.
As for the contrast between his performances on his team and in the selection, "it is a set", it has been justified.
"In Lille, I am all year round, which does not apply to Belgium.
"I have to get in position."
Called up to play Against Romania on Friday night, considering this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to finally "shine".
Not forgetting the "pleasure".
He has been cheering for the Bleus since he was seven years old, as well as during the victorious campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
"I've always been his fan," he says.
That will certainly reinforce especially the "particular" nature of the meeting.
Especially since he will face "Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami) ", remember.
"We just faced each other recently.
"Playing against them is always a joy."
Leekens has simply referred to "pride."
"Pride" for playing "a gala match."
"Pride" also to see, as a "neighbor", that France "returns to be a very high-level team", about a year after Knysna's trauma.
"Laurent Blanc has done a formidable job," he said enthusiastically.
While Belgium will not attend the next European competition, the technician would be happy to be able to share a plane with the Bleus towards... Brazil, in 2014.
"Our little Belgians are growing," he said.
"We are building something; players are ambitious, they're hungry.
"You'll be able to see it in the next few games." Including the match against France.
Portugal shows a lot of confidence
Paulo Bento's Portugal is facing with great optimism the back match against Bosnia (22h00), which will be held on Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first leg, both teams lacked realism.
"When these 90 minutes pass, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country."
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
He has no doubt; the Seleccao, which he has been running since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Indeed, only 90 minutes separate Portugal from happiness.
But there is a match to play and a rival, Bosnia, to defeat.
Considering the first leg (0-0), on Friday in Zenica's hell, it seems clear that things are not decided.
Portugal dominated the match for more than an hour, yes, but failed to score the valuable goal that would have given it peace of mind.
"It's a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven't scored away from home."
But at home, at Lisbon's bright Stadium of Light, the Portuguese are convinced that they will pass, in front of an audience that should be just as excited, even if it is clear that the match "is very evenly matched", dixit an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We hope the match is very evenly matched, but we are completely convinced that we can take the lead," said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
"We still have a 50% chance of participating in Euro 2012," carlos Queiroz's successor has nevertheless relativized.
Friday's tie in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
Bosnians could get a tie, though they also need to score.
"It's a good result, but at the same time it carries a risk, since we haven't scored away from home," Bento laments.
"We're going to play against a team that has great technical quality and has players with great individual quality," he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will go with the intention of exerting, from the beginning, maximum pressure on the Bosnians to "leave them no time to think".
A good idea, as long as, this time, it's realistic.